Stored Procedures

Why do we write function ? For code reusability

stored procedure is like  a function we use while coding

Create procedure name () ----> Takes 2 params , input param(explicitly define it while calling the func)  and output param (store the value)
begin
   select ------
   from  ----
   where ----
   / filters ---- 

end;

Calling a stored proce
: call procedure_name() 


Eg: 

Delimiter // ----> Syntax to just seperate the code for redability so that we understand that this is a stored procedure , we use this to differentiate btw multiple stored procedures or code chunks
create procedure sakila.TotalPaid(IN cid INT , OUT total Decimal(10,2))
    begin
   set @s = concat('Select count(*) as total_rows from ', tbl_namr
   prepare  stmt from @s;
   execute stmt ;
   deallocate prepare stmt ;
   end;
//  ---->   we use this to differentiate btw multiple stored procedures or code chunks , end with //






//

***   Dynamic SQL Procedure ****

create procedure sakila.DynamicQuery ( In tbl_name varchar(64))
 begin
   set @s = concat('Select count(*) as total_rows from ', tbl_name);
   prepare  stmt from @s;
   execute stmt ;
   deallocate prepare stmt ;
   end;

//




Calling :  --->  call sakila.GetCustomerPayments (7);
           --->  call sakila.TotalPaid(6 , @total) ; select @total ;
           --->  call sakila.DynamicQuery(sakila.payment);

** We can use stored tables to create multiple queries at once **

Meta data = information schema ( all info of tables , pks , fks)
































